## 1.7.1. End-to-End Value Increments (Vertical Slices)

‚ö†Ô∏è **Commands: story-shape**

**CRITICAL CONCEPT**: Increments MUST be designed as vertical slices that deliver end-to-end working flows across multiple features/epics, NOT horizontal layers that complete one feature/epic at a time.

**[DO]**:
* Design increments as VERTICAL SLICES across multiple epics/features (thin end-to-end flows)
* Ensure each increment delivers a complete working flow from start to finish
* Include PARTIAL features from multiple epics in each increment
* Build increments that demonstrate end-to-end capability (data entry ‚Üí processing ‚Üí validation ‚Üí persistence ‚Üí display)
* Start with simplest end-to-end flow (basic happy path for simplest user/scenario)
* Layer subsequent increments to add complexity, additional users, edge cases, variations
* Think "What's the thinnest slice that demonstrates the entire system working together?"

**[DON'T]**:
* Design increments as horizontal layers (complete Feature A, then Feature B, then Feature C)
* Build one epic/feature completely before touching another
* Create increments that only touch one area of the system
* Build increments that can't demonstrate working end-to-end flow
* Complete all features for one user type before starting another user type

**[Why This Matters]**:
* Enables early integration testing and risk reduction
* Provides working software sooner (can demo complete flow)
* Reveals integration issues early (not at the end)
* Allows for course correction based on real working system
* Delivers actual value (working flow) vs partial capability (one complete feature)

**[Examples]**:
* ‚úÖ **DO - Vertical Slice (End-to-End)**:
  ```
  Value Increment 1: Basic Character Creation Flow - NOW
    üéØ Epic: Create Character (PARTIAL - minimal creation)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Enter Basic Info (2 stories - name, archetype only)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Assign Abilities (1 story - simple point buy)
    üéØ Epic: Manage Character (PARTIAL - basic persistence)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Save Character (1 story - save to file)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Load Character (1 story - load from file)
    üéØ Epic: Display Character (PARTIAL - basic view)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: View Character Sheet (1 story - show basic info)
  
  Value Increment 2: Enhanced Character Options - NEXT
    üéØ Epic: Create Character (PARTIAL - add complexity)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Enter Basic Info (2 more stories - origin, description)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Assign Abilities (3 more stories - validation, limits, recalc)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Select Skills (4 stories - skill list, ranks, specialties)
    üéØ Epic: Manage Character (PARTIAL - add features)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Save Character (1 story - auto-save)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Export Character (2 stories - PDF, share)
    üéØ Epic: Display Character (PARTIAL - richer display)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: View Character Sheet (2 stories - skills section, calculated values)
  ```
  ‚úÖ **Why**: Each increment delivers COMPLETE END-TO-END flow. Increment 1 = basic creation ‚Üí save ‚Üí load ‚Üí view. Increment 2 builds on that working foundation.

* ‚ùå **DON'T - Horizontal Layer (Feature-by-Feature)**:
  ```
  Value Increment 1: Character Creation - NOW
    üéØ Epic: Create Character (COMPLETE)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Enter Basic Info (ALL stories)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Assign Abilities (ALL stories)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Select Skills (ALL stories)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Choose Powers (ALL stories)
  
  Value Increment 2: Character Management - NEXT
    üéØ Epic: Manage Character (COMPLETE)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Save Character (ALL stories)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Load Character (ALL stories)
      ‚öôÔ∏è Feature: Export Character (ALL stories)
  ```
  ‚ùå **Why**: Increment 1 can't be tested end-to-end (no save/load). Can't deliver working software until Increment 2. Integration risks discovered late.

**[Layering Strategy]**:
* **Increment 1**: Simplest user + simplest scenario + happy path only ‚Üí Full end-to-end
* **Increment 2**: Add complexity (more options, validations) + Additional user types ‚Üí Full end-to-end
* **Increment 3**: Add edge cases + Error handling + Advanced features ‚Üí Full end-to-end
* **Increment 4**: Add variations + Alternative flows + Optimizations ‚Üí Full end-to-end

**[Integration Points to Consider]**:
Each increment should demonstrate these end-to-end concerns (even if minimal):
* Data entry/input
* Business logic/processing
* Validation/error handling
* Persistence/storage
* Retrieval/loading
* Display/output

